    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm working on an embedded C++ project for an automotive ECU and I'm hitting a wall. We're seeing a slow memory leak where the available RAM gradually exhausts over about 4-6 hours of operation. \n\nI've checked most of the main loops, but I can't find the culprit. Here is a snippet of the telemetry handling class where I suspect something might be going on:\n\n```cpp\nvoid TelemetryManager::processBuffer(const uint8_t* data, size_t len) {\n    // Allocating buffer for incoming packet processing\n    uint8_t* packetBuffer = new uint8_t[len];\n    memcpy(packetBuffer, data, len);\n\n    if (validateChecksum(packetBuffer, len)) {\n        updateSystemState(packetBuffer, len);\n    } else {\n        logError(\"Checksum mismatch\");\n        // Need to ensure this doesn't leak if validation fails\n    }\n\n    // Log the packet size for telemetry\n    this->history.push_back(len);\n    \n    // TODO: Cleanup logic needed here\n}\n```\n\nCan you give me a systematic approach to locating where this leak is coming from in a resource-constrained environment like this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A memory leak in an ECU, especially one that creeps up like a slow, persistent drip, is almost certainly a case of forgetting to clean up after a successful or failed operation. You've hit the classic \"forgot to call `delete[]`\" problem, which is almost certainly the cause here. You must ensure that every time you call `new`, you eventually call `delete`.\n\nIn your snippet, you are allocating `packetBuffer` with `new uint8_t[len]`, but you never deallocate it before the function exits. Even if the checksum fails, the memory is still allocated and never freed. The cleanup logic you noted as `// TODO: Cleanup logic needed here` is where the missing `delete[] packetBuffer;` belongs, and it needs to happen regardless of the validation outcome.\n\nFor a systematic approach in a resource-constrained environment, you should adopt a strict pattern: **RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization)**. Instead of raw pointers and manual `new`/`delete`, use smart pointers or, even better for embedded systems, fixed-size buffers or stack allocation where possible. If you must use dynamic allocation, wrap it in a class that guarantees cleanup in its destructor.\n\nHere is",
      "source": "target",
